<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41138289</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>29</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>29</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1773-0597</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>48</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal francais d'ophtalmologie</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Fr Ophtalmol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Safety and efficacy of quercetin as an alternative to riboflavin in collagen cross-linking treatment.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>104667</StartPage><MedlinePgn>104667</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.jfo.2025.104667</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0181-5512(25)00249-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To evaluate the safety and efficacy of quercetin as an alternative to riboflavin in collagen cross-linking (CXL) treatment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Australia-New Zealand rabbits (n=60) were divided into four groups: a control group (C group; no UVA exposure), a Tween 20 buffer group (T group; UVA irradiated), a riboflavin group (R group; UVA irradiated with riboflavin), and a quercetin group (Q group; UVA irradiated with quercetin). The corneal tissues were analyzed histologically and biomechanically on days 7 and 42 post-treatment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The biomechanical tests demonstrated a 50% increase in Young's modulus and a 21% increase in tensile strength in the R group compared to controls (P&lt;0.05), confirming significant corneal stiffening. In contrast, the Q group showed an 18% increase in Young's modulus, but this was not statistically significant compared to controls (P&gt;0.05). Histological analysis revealed no inflammation, corneal edema, or endothelial damage in any group. Keratocyte apoptosis was detected in the anterior stroma of the R and Q groups at day 7, with repopulation occurring by day 42.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">While quercetin demonstrated some biomechanical effects; its impact on corneal stiffening was significantly lower than that of riboflavin, indicating its inefficacy as a photo-induced cross-linking agent.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Masson SAS. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Katre</LastName><ForeName>B</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Kocaeli State Hospital, Department of Ophthalmology, Kocaeli, T&#xfc;rkiye.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Alt&#x131;nta&#x15f;</LastName><ForeName>&#xd6;</ForeName><Initials>&#xd6;</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Acibadem Mehmet Ali Ayd&#x131;nlar University, Department of Ophthalmology, &#x130;stanbul, T&#xfc;rkiye.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Emre</LastName><ForeName>E</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Kocaeli Derince Training and Research Hospital, Kocaeli, T&#xfc;rkiye.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>&#x15e;&#x131;k Sarman</LastName><ForeName>Z</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Buyukcekmece State Hospital, Department of Ophthalmology, Istanbul, T&#xfc;rkiye.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cengiz</LastName><ForeName>A</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Kocaeli University, School of Technical Training, Department of Machine Training, Kocaeli, T&#xfc;rkiye.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y